  <h1>About productliabilitycalc.com</h1>
  <p><em>Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>productliabilitycalc.com is an informational reference for consumers who have been injured by a defective product. The center of the site is a calculator that produces an estimated recovery range based on defect theory, product category, injury severity, jurisdiction, and a handful of demographic and economic inputs. The calculator is supported by a methodology page that explains the underlying math, a set of guides that explain the legal landscape in plain English, and a case-types reference that walks through the major industries where product liability claims arise.</p>

  <h2>Why this site exists</h2>

  <p>Product liability is one of the more technical practice areas in personal injury law. The combination of strict liability, the three defect theories, state-by-state damages caps, federal preemption questions, statutes of repose, and mass-tort treatment makes it difficult for a layperson to get oriented after an injury. Existing online resources fall into two camps: law-firm marketing pages that funnel toward a free consultation without explaining anything, and dense academic treatments that assume legal training. There is a real gap in the middle for clear, accurate, free reference material.</p>

  <p>This site fills that gap. The calculator is meant to give a reader a realistic, defensible estimate of what their case is worth, so that the first conversation with a lawyer can start somewhere other than zero. The guides are meant to be the kind of explanation a paralegal would give a new client over coffee &mdash; accurate, practical, and free of marketing.</p>

  <h2>Who runs it</h2>

  <p>The site is published by The Click Lab, an independent web publisher that operates a small network of legal-reference calculators (catastrophic injury, employment law, consumer law). The editorial team is led by Auden Cordell (Product Liability Practice Lead) with contributions from Holland Devlin (Recall and Consumer Safety Reference). Neither is a licensed attorney; both are paralegals with focused experience in product liability and consumer protection. Full bios and editorial standards are on the <a href="/editorial">editorial page</a>.</p>

  <h2>What this site is</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>An informational reference written for consumers, not lawyers.</li>
    <li>A calculator with documented, auditable methodology.</li>
    <li>A set of guides on the legal framework and the practical steps after an injury.</li>
    <li>A free resource, supported by Google AdSense, with no signup, no email collection, no funnel.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What this site is not</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>It is not a law firm. The contributors do not represent readers.</li>
    <li>It is not legal advice. Nothing on the site substitutes for consultation with a licensed product liability attorney in the reader's state.</li>
    <li>It is not a referral service. We do not refer readers to specific law firms or charge for case leads.</li>
    <li>It is not exhaustive. State-specific rules, federal-preemption arguments, and case-specific facts all matter; the calculator captures the most important factors but cannot replace individualized legal analysis.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to use it</h2>

  <p>For most readers, the right starting point is the <a href="/">home-page calculator</a>. Enter your facts, run the estimate, and read the explanatory text below the form. From there, the <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> page explains how the estimate is computed, the <a href="/case-types">case-types</a> page walks through the major product categories, and the <a href="/guides">guides</a> answer the most common follow-up questions. If you are unsure how product liability differs from ordinary personal injury, the <a href="/faq">FAQ</a> is a fast overview.</p>

  <p>For comments, corrections, or licensing inquiries, contact us at <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We respond to genuine corrections quickly and welcome them.</p>
</BaseLayout>
